---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Understanding Parental Alienation"
  description="Part I: Understanding Parental Alienation — what it is, how it works, why it happens, and what the research shows. Articles and resources by Malcolm Smith."
>
  <section class="section section-dark hub-hero">
    <div class="container-narrow" style="text-align:center;">
      <p class="part-label">Part I</p>
      <h1>Understanding<br />Parental Alienation</h1>
      <p class="hub-intro">
        What is happening. Why it happens. What the research shows — and what it misses.
        Evidence-based, compassionate, and honest.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Overview -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container-narrow prose">
      <p class="lead-text">
        Understanding parental alienation — what it actually is, how it works psychologically,
        and why institutions so often fail to recognise or address it — is the foundation of
        everything else. You cannot fight what you don't understand.
      </p>
      <p>
        This section draws on decades of academic research, clinical frameworks, and
        Malcolm's own ten-year experience to give you the clearest possible picture
        of what is happening in your family — and why.
      </p>
      <p>
        The goal is not just knowledge. It is the kind of understanding that replaces
        confusion with clarity, self-blame with recognition, and isolation with the
        realisation that this is a documented, studied, and increasingly acknowledged
        phenomenon affecting millions of families worldwide.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Topic cards -->
  <section class="section section-alt">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="section-eyebrow">Topics covered</p>
      <h2 class="section-heading">What you'll find here</h2>
      <div class="topics-grid">
        <div class="topic-card card">
          <h3>The Signs</h3>
          <p>
            How to distinguish deliberate alienation from normal post-separation conflict.
            Gardner's eight behavioural manifestations, the Five-Factor Model, and what
            to watch for in your child's words and behaviour.
          </p>
          <a href="/articles/signs-of-parental-alienation" class="topic-link">Read the article →</a>
        </div>
        <div class="topic-card card">
          <h3>The System</h3>
          <p>
            Alienation is not a one-person act. It involves the alienating parent, the child,
            enablers, extended family, and — too often — the professional system itself.
            Understanding who plays what role changes everything.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="topic-card card">
          <h3>The Tactics</h3>
          <p>
            The 17 tactics of alienation identified by Dr Amy Baker — from badmouthing and
            gatekeeping to loyalty traps and identity manipulation. Recognising them is the
            first step to countering them.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="topic-card card">
          <h3>The Research</h3>
          <p>
            What peer-reviewed studies actually show: the scale of the problem (22 million
            children affected), long-term harm to children, and why the legal system
            consistently falls behind the science.
          </p>
          <a href="/you-are-not-alone" class="topic-link">See the data →</a>
        </div>
        <div class="topic-card card">
          <h3>The Child's Experience</h3>
          <p>
            Your child is not choosing this freely. The Systemic Conditioning Model explains
            how external pressure creates an internal survival crisis — forcing psychological
            splitting as a coping mechanism, not a genuine preference.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="topic-card card">
          <h3>The Trauma</h3>
          <p>
            The 2D Alienation Trauma Pain Model maps the targeted parent's suffering across
            four levels of heartbreak and eight amplification factors. Understanding your
            own pain is not self-indulgence — it is survival.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Key insight -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container-narrow prose">
      <h2>Why understanding matters</h2>
      <blockquote class="pull-quote">
        "Parental alienation is not a custody dispute. It is a recognised form of
        psychological violence and coercive control that causes profound, multi-layered
        trauma — to both parent and child."
      </blockquote>
      <p>
        When you first experience alienation, the confusion is overwhelming. Your child
        says things that make no sense. Professionals who should help seem unable to see
        what is happening. Friends and family suggest you must have done something wrong.
        The isolation compounds the pain.
      </p>
      <p>
        Understanding changes the equation. When you can name what is happening — when you
        can see the patterns, the tactics, the systemic failures — you stop blaming yourself
        for something that was done to you. You stop expecting the system to rescue you on
        its own timeline. And you start making decisions from clarity rather than desperation.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is not about becoming an expert in alienation theory. It is about having enough
        knowledge to protect yourself, advocate for your child, and communicate what is
        happening to the professionals and people in your life who need to understand it.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Articles preview -->
  <section class="section section-alt">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="section-eyebrow">Articles</p>
      <h2 class="section-heading">Start reading</h2>
      <div class="articles-preview">
        <article class="article-preview-card card">
          <span class="article-tag">Understanding PA</span>
          <h3><a href="/articles/signs-of-parental-alienation">Signs of Parental Alienation: What to Look For and What It Means</a></h3>
          <p>
            The patterns that indicate deliberate alienation versus normal post-separation
            conflict — and why distinguishing them matters for your strategy.
          </p>
          <span class="article-meta">8 min read</span>
        </article>
      </div>
      <p style="margin-top:2rem;">
        More articles are being published regularly.
        <a href="/articles">See all articles →</a>
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CTA -->
  <section class="section section-dark" style="text-align:center;">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <h2>Start with the free guide</h2>
      <p style="opacity:0.8; margin-bottom:2rem; max-width:540px; margin-inline:auto;">
        The Survival Guide distils the most immediately useful frameworks and practical
        advice into a single resource you can use today.
      </p>
      <div style="display:flex; gap:1rem; justify-content:center; flex-wrap:wrap;">
        <a href="/free-guide" class="btn btn-primary">Get the Free Guide</a>
        <a href="/survival-guide" class="btn btn-outline-light">Part II: Survival Guide →</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

</BaseLayout>

<style>
.hub-hero { padding-block: 6rem; }
.part-label {
  font-size: 0.78rem;
  font-weight: 600;
  letter-spacing: 0.12em;
  text-transform: uppercase;
  color: var(--color-amber-light);
  margin-bottom: 1rem;
}
.hub-intro {
  font-size: 1.1rem;
  color: rgba(247,243,238,0.8);
  margin-top: 1.25rem;
  line-height: 1.75;
}
.lead-text {
  font-size: 1.15rem;
  line-height: 1.75;
  color: var(--color-charcoal);
  margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
}
.section-eyebrow {
  font-size: 0.78rem;
  font-weight: 600;
  letter-spacing: 0.1em;
  text-transform: uppercase;
  color: var(--color-amber);
  margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
}
.section-heading {
  margin-bottom: 2rem;
}

.topics-grid {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
  gap: 1.5rem;
}
.topic-card {
  padding: 2rem;
}
.topic-card h3 {
  font-size: 1.15rem;
  margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
  color: var(--color-green-deep);
}
.topic-card p {
  font-size: 0.92rem;
  line-height: 1.7;
  color: var(--color-charcoal);
  margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
}
.topic-link {
  font-size: 0.85rem;
  font-weight: 600;
  color: var(--color-amber);
  text-decoration: none;
}
.topic-link:hover { color: var(--color-green-deep); }

.articles-preview {
  max-width: 680px;
}
.article-preview-card {
  padding: 2rem;
}
.article-preview-card h3 {
  font-size: 1.1rem;
  margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
}
.article-preview-card h3 a {
  color: var(--color-green-deep);
  text-decoration: none;
}
.article-preview-card h3 a:hover { color: var(--color-amber); }
.article-preview-card p {
  font-size: 0.92rem;
  line-height: 1.7;
  color: var(--color-charcoal);
}
.article-tag {
  font-size: 0.72rem;
  font-weight: 600;
  letter-spacing: 0.06em;
  text-transform: uppercase;
  color: var(--color-amber);
  background: rgba(196,154,60,0.1);
  border-radius: 4px;
  padding: 0.2em 0.6em;
  display: inline-block;
  margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
}
.article-meta {
  font-size: 0.82rem;
  color: var(--color-warm-grey);
  margin-top: 0.5rem;
}

@media (max-width: 900px) {
  .topics-grid { grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr); }
}
@media (max-width: 600px) {
  .topics-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
}
</style>
